Phase 2: Firewall & Network Security Fundamentals (Weeks 5‚Äì8)
Goal: Learn firewall basics, VPNs, and security monitoring.

Week 5: Firewalls
Theory:
What is a firewall? Packet filtering vs Stateful
Fortinet/Cisco/Palo Alto firewall basics
Security zones and policies

Lab:
Configure a basic FortiGate firewall
config system interface
    edit "port1"
        set ip 192.168.1.1/24
        set allowaccess ping https ssh
    next
end

config firewall policy
    edit 1
        set srcintf "port1"
        set dstintf "port2"
        set srcaddr "all"
        set dstaddr "all"
        set action accept
    next
end



Below is a simple, working example of eBGP configuration between two Juniper (vMX/vSRX) routers in EVE-NG using Junos OS.

Topology
R1 (AS 65001) -------- R2 (AS 65002)
        ge-0/0/0      ge-0/0/0
     10.0.12.1/30   10.0.12.2/30

Router 1 (R1) Configuration
AS: 65001
Interface IP: 10.0.12.1/30
Advertised network: 1.1.1.0/24


configure
set system host-name R1
set interfaces ge-0/0/0 unit 0 family inet address 10.0.12.1/30
set interfaces lo0 unit 0 family inet address 1.1.1.1/32
set routing-options autonomous-system 65001
set protocols bgp group EBGP-R2 type external
set protocols bgp group EBGP-R2 peer-as 65002
set protocols bgp group EBGP-R2 neighbor 10.0.12.2

set policy-options policy-statement EXPORT-LOOPBACK term 1 from route-filter 1.1.1.0/24 exact
set policy-options policy-statement EXPORT-LOOPBACK term 1 then accept
set policy-options policy-statement EXPORT-LOOPBACK then reject
set protocols bgp group EBGP-R2 export EXPORT-LOOPBACK
commit

Router 2 (R2) Configuration
AS: 65002
Interface IP: 10.0.12.2/30
Advertised network: 2.2.2.0/24

configure
set system host-name R2
set interfaces ge-0/0/0 unit 0 family inet address 10.0.12.2/30
set interfaces lo0 unit 0 family inet address 2.2.2.2/32
set routing-options autonomous-system 65002
set protocols bgp group EBGP-R1 type external
set protocols bgp group EBGP-R1 peer-as 65001
set protocols bgp group EBGP-R1 neighbor 10.0.12.1

set policy-options policy-statement EXPORT-LOOPBACK term 1 from route-filter 2.2.2.0/24 exact
set policy-options policy-statement EXPORT-LOOPBACK term 1 then accept
set policy-options policy-statement EXPORT-LOOPBACK then reject
set protocols bgp group EBGP-R1 export EXPORT-LOOPBACK
commit

Verification Commands (on both routers)
show bgp neighbor
show bgp summary
show route protocol bgp
ping 2.2.2.2 source 1.1.1.1

Expected Result
BGP state: Established
R1 learns 2.2.2.0/24 via BGP
R2 learns 1.1.1.0/24 via BGP
Successful ping between loopbacks
If you want:
iBGP configuration
BGP with loopback peering
BGP authentication
Route-reflector or multihop setup
Tell me and I‚Äôll tailor it for your lab üëç




Week 6: VPNs
Theory:
Types: Site-to-Site, Remote Access VPN
IPSec vs SSL VPN
Authentication methods (PSK, certificates)

Lab:


Configure site-to-site VPN between two Cisco routers
crypto isakmp policy 10
 encryption aes
 hash sha
 authentication pre-share
 group 2
crypto isakmp key MySecretKey address 192.168.2.1
crypto ipsec transform-set MySET esp-aes esp-sha-hmac
crypto map VPN 10 ipsec-isakmp
 set peer 192.168.2.1
 set transform-set MySET
 match address 101
interface g0/0
 crypto map VPN




Week 7: IDS/IPS & Threat Detection
Theory:
IDS vs IPS
Signatures and anomaly detection
Common attacks (DoS, MITM, brute force)

Lab:

Configure basic Snort IDS on Linux
sudo apt install snort -y
sudo snort -A console -c /etc/snort/snort.conf -i eth0




Week 8: Security Monitoring Tools
Theory:
SolarWinds, Netcool, Nagios, PRTG basics
Event logs, SNMP, Syslog
Lab:

Install Nagios Core and monitor a host
sudo apt install nagios4 nagios-plugins -y
sudo systemctl start nagios4
sudo systemctl enable nagios4
# Access web UI at http://<server-ip>/nagios4

